p.quote:
You are laughing at yourself: you did not prepare the young man nor did you
ascertain whether he was able to understand these matters;
but perhaps, you are only employing him as a reader.

note.#text:
There is some deficiency in the text.  (Acad. Prior. i. 12),
but enim necesse est lancem in libra ponderibus impositis deprimi;
sic snimum perspicuis cedere,' appears to supply the deficiency.

Socrates' wife Xanthippe is charged by her eldest son Lamprocles
with being so ill-tempered as to be past all endurance (Xenophon,
). Xenophon in this chapter has reported the conversation of Socrates with his son on this matter.

' The youth, probably, means the scholar, who neglects neatness;
and the old man, the tutor, that gives him no precept or example of it.'
Mrs. Carter.

div2.p:
When a young man was boasting in the theatre and saying, I am wise, for I have conversed with many wise men;
Epictetus said, I also have conversed with many rich
men, but I am not rich.

p.#text:
Quum de animarum agitur salute ac de respectu nostri;
'aliquid et sine ratione faciendum est,' ut Epictetum
dixisse approbat Arrianus.

from Oral Recitation,
private MSS., Broadsides, &c. Edit. by
R. Bell.

